{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01BxnTJyJjFHjLcyCQ4MBrRL","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The Next.js server started successfully on port 3099, but the curl failed with 000 (connection failed). Wait, but the server shows \"Ready in 216ms\". The curl failed with 000, which might mean the connection was refused. Let me check what happened.\n\nActually, looking at the curl command - I used `-o /dev/null` which suppresses the output, but `-w \"%{http_code}\"` would show 000 if the connection failed. But the server says \"Ready\"...\n\nWait, the issue might be that the curl tried to connect before the server was ready, and my 8 second wait was already past by the time the curl ran. \n\nThe server started in 216ms, so the curl should have connected. But a 000 error with SSE means the connection failed entirely—not a timeout. The curl with `--max-time 5` on an SSE endpoint would normally connect but then hang on the streaming response, so 000 suggests the connection was refused outright. This could be a port conflict or the server isn't actually listening on 3099.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1162,"cache_read_input_tokens":50290,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1162},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a5aaa11d-67a7-4ffc-9b3b-2cb42566b1cb","uuid":"e21535ea-e074-4a7f-a251-38453ad4ea9e"}
