{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_0164X6tE8cwPkT3B6xbyjNgH","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! The Next.js log shows:\n```\nGET /api/live 200 in 3.0s (next.js: 1277µs, application-code: 3.0s)\n```\n\nThis means the route returned 200, but the curl timed out at 3 seconds. The issue is:\n1. The Next.js server processed the request\n2. The response was 200\n3. But the curl timed out because it received 0 bytes\n\nWait... the log says \"200 in 3.0s\" but curl received 0 bytes. This suggests that the response headers WERE sent (200 status), but curl expected to also receive response headers in verbose mode but got nothing before the timeout.\n\n\nActually, looking at the curl output more carefully, the request was sent but curl never received any response bytes before timing out. The server logged a 200 status, but the response headers were never actually transmitted to the client—the server-side timing doesn't match what the client experienced.\n\nThis points to a real issue: the route returns a `ReadableStream` body, but in Next.js the headers might not be sent until the first chunk of data arrives. Since ClickHouse is unavailable and never sends data, the headers get stuck in a buffer and never reach the client. The server thinks it completed the request, but from the client's perspective, nothing came back.\n\nI'm wondering if this is specific to Turbopack in development mode—maybe it's buffering the entire response before flushing it, or the SSE headers aren't being properly flushed when there's no body data. According to HTTP/1.1, headers should go out immediately regardless of body content, so this feels like a Next.js or Node.js buffering behavior that's causing the problem.\n\nThe real issue is that the server takes 3 seconds to respond (matching the curl timeout), which means it's waiting for the first stream chunk before sending headers—and since ClickHouse is unavailable and errors are being swallowed, no data ever arrives, so the headers never get sent.\n\nEven if ClickHouse were available, the headers-on-first-chunk approach would be problematic for SSE clients that expect immediate header confirmation. Though in practice, with a 1-second polling interval, the first event would arrive quickly enough for the \"live feed\" use case. The real problem surfaces when ClickHouse is down—the client hangs indefinitely waiting for that first byte.\n\nThe sprint contract test is checking whether the endpoint returns the proper `Content-Type: text/event-stream` header, which it currently fails because the headers never get sent when the stream has no data.\n\nExamining the route handler more closely...\n\nStill writing handler logic...\n\nThe core problem is that headers don't get sent until data is actually enqueued to the stream. Even if ClickHouse is running and returning results, if there are no new events, nothing gets sent and the client never receives the response headers. This is a fundamental flaw in the SSE implementation—headers should be flushed immediately, and the connection should stay alive with periodic comment pings rather than waiting for data.\n\nLet me reconsider whether Next.js actually buffers headers or if something else is happening. Looking at the curl output showing zero bytes received, it seems like nothing is being sent at all, which suggests the headers really aren't being flushed until the first data chunk arrives.\n\nThis is a real issue for the HTTP contract check, which specifically validates that `Content-Type: text/event-stream` is present in the response headers. But I'm wondering if this actually matters for the browser's EventSource behavior—when a browser connects to `/api/live`, it can wait for data even if headers arrive with the first chunk. The real question is whether the sprint contract's HTTP check is something we need to satisfy or if it's acceptable for the browser use case.\n\nLet me reconsider the TCP/HTTP mechanics here: the server should send headers immediately when the response begins, regardless of whether body data is ready. In Node.js, headers get flushed to the client as soon as you start writing, so the EventSource should receive the `Content-Type` header right away, not wait for data to be enqueued.\n\nLooking at the Next.js server logs more carefully, the timing breakdown is interesting—the \"application-code: 3.0s\" duration likely represents how long my streaming handler ran before the connection was terminated, not necessarily a buffering issue. This suggests the dev server might be handling streams differently than production would.\n\nThe real problem is that headers aren't being sent immediately when the SSE connection opens. According to the spec, clients need to see the Content-Type header right away to confirm they've got a valid event stream, not just a hanging connection. I could fix this by sending an SSE comment as a keep-alive ping in the initial callback to force the headers out, but since this is a QA evaluation rather than an implementation task, I should just flag it as a bug. The sprint contract specifically requires that GET request to return a response with the text/event-stream Content-Type header, and that's currently failing.\n\nThe issue compounds when ClickHouse is unavailable—the stream never generates any data, so the headers never get flushed to the client, and curl just times out. This could be a Turbopack dev server quirk though, so let me test with the production build using `next start` to see if the behavior changes.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1126,"cache_read_input_tokens":52916,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1126},"output_tokens":59,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":