{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01ERyqmdS1TY4UccDqCE9qMG","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The production mode also fails! This confirms it's a real implementation bug, not a dev-mode issue.\n\nThe problem: When `GET /api/live` is called, the route handler creates a `ReadableStream` and returns a `Response` with SSE headers. However, because the stream doesn't immediately produce data (it polls every 1 second and all errors are swallowed), the HTTP response headers are never sent to the client.\n\nIn HTTP/1.1, the response headers should be sent as soon as the server starts sending data. The behavior here is that Node.js/Next.js buffers the response headers until the first chunk of the body is ready. \n\nThe root cause is that the SSE stream never produces any data—either because ClickHouse is unavailable or because there are no new events within the first polling interval. Without that initial data chunk, the headers get stuck in the buffer. The fix is to immediately enqueue an SSE comment in the stream's start callback to flush those headers right away, rather than waiting for actual events to arrive.\n\nNow I'm checking the test results—all unit tests pass, but the linter is reporting some warnings. I need to verify whether these are pre-existing issues or new ones introduced by my changes, and what the actual exit code was.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":874,"cache_read_input_tokens":56986,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":874},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a5aaa11d-67a7-4ffc-9b3b-2cb42566b1cb","uuid":"6a81a4b1-fc9e-4a6f-b858-7f54e05296fd"}
