{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Y8GXrWCuJhFxgsU788yuwn","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. The lint:fix doesn't change anything and exits with 0. The 4 warnings are pre-existing (in seed.test.ts) and not introduced by F17.\n\nNow let me summarize the evaluation:\n\n**Phase A checks:**\n1. ✅ File `src/lib/live.ts` exists and exports `queryNewEvents`\n2. ✅ File `src/app/api/live/route.ts` exists and exports `GET`\n3. ✅ Test suite: 259 passed, 25 skipped (0 failures)\n4. ✅ Lint: exit 0, 4 pre-existing warnings in seed.test.ts, 0 new warnings\n\n\n5. ✅ Type check: exit 0\n6. ✅ Build: exit 0, `/api/live` listed as dynamic route\n\n**Phase B checks:**\n7. ❌ HTTP check: GET http://localhost:3099/api/live returns 0 bytes because the ReadableStream never produces data when ClickHouse is unavailable, so Next.js doesn't flush the response headers including `Content-Type: text/event-stream` until the first chunk arrives.\n\nThe root issue is that the implementation waits for ClickHouse to return data before sending anything to the client.  The fix would be to immediately send an SSE comment to flush headers. This is a real bug—even with ClickHouse working, if there are no new events in the first polling cycle, the client hangs for a second, and when ClickHouse errors occur (silently caught), the client never gets a response at all.\n\nThe plan did flag \"Full end-to-end SSE streaming\" as an integration gap, but the HTTP header check itself isn't marked as one—it's a regular sprint criterion.\n\n**Score: 7/10** — Unit, type, lint, and build checks all pass; the HTTP check fails due to missing SSE header flushing.\n\nThis is a NEEDS_WORK verdict. The fix is straightforward, but it's a genuine bug. I should also write integration tests to catch this, though the full end-to-end streaming test would require ClickHouse running. I can still write a test that verifies the SSE header flushing behavior without needing the full database setup.\n\nThe unit tests pass because they're calling the route directly and checking the Response object's headers, which are correctly set. But at the HTTP level, those headers never actually reach the client until the first byte of body content is written. The bug only surfaces when testing actual HTTP behavior, not when inspecting the Response object in isolation.\n\nSince ClickHouse isn't running, I can't write a meaningful integration test for the full streaming flow. I'll document in the eval that the HTTP check caught the bug, note why no integration tests were added, and provide specific guidance on fixing it.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":254,"cache_read_input_tokens":59238,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":254},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a5aaa11d-67a7-4ffc-9b3b-2cb42566b1cb","uuid":"41dc5925-ce33-420f-81c3-93415827a611"}
